Your state is now being saved and found:

```text
Saving auth transaction key=auth:state:...
lookup auth transaction key=auth:state:..., found=true
```

But then it fails with:

```text
java.util.LinkedHashMap incompatible with com.bnpp.pf.arthur.core.model.AuthTransaction
```

So Redis is returning data, but your code is doing a direct cast and getting a `LinkedHashMap` instead of an `AuthTransaction`.

# Why this happens

With your current serializer setup, the stored JSON is being deserialized as a generic map, not your class.

So this line in `findByState()` is the problem:

```java
return (AuthTransaction) value;
```

# Fastest fix

Convert the map into `AuthTransaction` with `ObjectMapper`.

## Update `RedisAuthTransactionService`

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
@Slf4j
public class RedisAuthTransactionService {

    private static final String PREFIX = "auth:state:";

    private final RedisTemplate<String, Object> redisTemplate;
    private final ObjectMapper objectMapper;

    public void save(AuthTransaction tx) {
        String key = PREFIX + tx.getState();
        log.info("Saving auth transaction key={}", key);
        redisTemplate.opsForValue().set(key, tx, Duration.ofMinutes(5));
    }

    public AuthTransaction findByState(String state) {
        String key = PREFIX + state;
        Object value = redisTemplate.opsForValue().get(key);

        log.info("lookup auth transaction key={}, found={}", key, value != null);

        if (value == null) {
            return null;
        }

        if (value instanceof AuthTransaction tx) {
            return tx;
        }

        if (value instanceof Map<?, ?>) {
            return objectMapper.convertValue(value, AuthTransaction.class);
        }

        throw new IllegalStateException("Unexpected auth transaction type: " + value.getClass().getName());
    }

    public void delete(String state) {
        redisTemplate.delete(PREFIX + state);
    }
}
```

# Also do this once

Your Redis may still contain older values from previous serializer attempts. Clear it once:

```bash
redis-cli FLUSHALL
```

Or just delete the auth keys:

```bash
redis-cli KEYS "auth:state:*"
redis-cli DEL auth:state:...
```

# Best long-term fix

A cleaner version is to use a dedicated typed serializer/template for `AuthTransaction`, but the `objectMapper.convertValue(...)` fix is the quickest way to unblock you now.

